</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="361" type="reference_group">
<paragraph pageId="14" pageNumber="361">
<taxonomicName authority="Le Peletier &amp; Audinet-Serville, 1828" authorityName="Le Peletier &amp; Audinet-Serville" authorityYear="1828" class="Insecta" family="Tenthredinidae" genus="Empria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Empria tridentis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="361" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tridentis">Empria tridentis</taxonomicName>
Lee &amp; Ryu, 1996: 23. Type locality: South-Korea, Goseong-gun Hyangnobong, 38.3167N 128.3E. Holotype female, YUIC [examined].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="361" type="taxonomic affinities">
<paragraph pageId="14" pageNumber="361">Taxonomic affinities.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="14" pageNumber="361">
Morphologically, no close relatives can be identified, but in the phylogenetic analysis of the ITS and mtDNA sequences combined, the species appears as a sister of the longicornis-group (Fig. 40). Superficially may resemble 
<taxonomicName authority="Le Peletier &amp; Audinet-Serville, 1828" authorityName="Le Peletier &amp; Audinet-Serville" authorityYear="1828" class="Insecta" family="Tenthredinidae" genus="Empria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Empria longicornis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="361" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longicornis">Empria longicornis</taxonomicName>
, from which 
<taxonomicName authority="Le Peletier &amp; Audinet-Serville, 1828" authorityName="Le Peletier &amp; Audinet-Serville" authorityYear="1828" class="Insecta" family="Tenthredinidae" genus="Empria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Empria tridentis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="361" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tridentis">Empria tridentis</taxonomicName>
can easily be distinguished by tegulae, base of metatibia, trochanters, and trochantelli pale (all black in 
<taxonomicName authority="Le Peletier &amp; Audinet-Serville, 1828" authorityName="Le Peletier &amp; Audinet-Serville" authorityYear="1828" class="Insecta" family="Tenthredinidae" genus="Empria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Empria longicornis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="361" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longicornis">Empria longicornis</taxonomicName>
), and by very different structure of lancets and penis valves.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="361" type="host plants">
<paragraph pageId="14" pageNumber="361">Host plants.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="14" pageNumber="361">Unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="361" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="14" pageNumber="361">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="14" pageNumber="361">East Palaearctic. Specimens studied are from Japan (Hokkaido, Honshu), Russia (Khabarovsk Krai, Primorsky Krai), and South-Korea.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="361" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="14" pageNumber="361">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="14" pageNumber="361">
The original description of this species states that there are &quot;a pair of large flecks on lateral portion of 
<normalizedToken originalValue="lstâ€“">lst-</normalizedToken>
4th tergite&quot; (
<bibRefCitation author="Lee, J-W" journalOrPublisher="Entomological Research Bulletin" pageId="17" pageNumber="364" pagination="17 - 34" title="A Systematic Study on the Tenthredinidae (Hymenoptera: Symphyta) from Korea II. Ten new species of the Tenthredinidae." volume="22" year="1996">Lee and Ryu 1996</bibRefCitation>
), while actually no specimen studied (including the holotype) has pale patches (&quot;large flecks&quot;) on first tergite. There is one male (NSMT018) from Honshu (Nagano) with penis valve slightly different (see http://www.morphbank.net/?id=592669) from all the other studied males, but the material is currently insufficient to decide if the specimen is aberrant or represents a separate (sibling) species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
